article.description: Rasheed Wallace collected 23 points and 14 rebounds as the Portland Trail Blazers handed the Pacers their ninth loss in 10 games, 94-80.
article.headline: Pacers don't expect to have Artest in Sacramento
article.linkText: Artest suspended one game after latest flagrant foul
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Ron Artest got back into trouble and the struggling Indiana Pacers got another loss.
Artest

Artest was suspended one game after being charged with a flagrant foul Saturday night in the Pacers' 94-80 loss to the Portland Trail Blazers. That's not good for the Pacers, who have won just one of their last 10 games and have lost eight straight on the road. Artest, second on the team in scoring, was called for a flagrant foul on Bonzi Wells early in the second quarter. Artest -- who now has six flagrant foul points -- was suspended for Sunday's game against the Kings. After the game, Artest was careful and clipped with his answers to questions about the foul. "I can't really call it," he said. "You can't question a referee." With seven straight losses against Western Conference teams, the Pacers need Artest. "We need to pull together without him," Jermaine O'Neal said. "But him being gone is not our problem. We've got to decide if we want to be a sixth or seventh seed, or the No. 1 seed in the East." After O'Neal's hook shot tied it at 20 with 3:20 left in the first quarter, ex-Pacer Dale Davis answered with a layup to put Portland back ahead. The Blazers led the rest of the way. Rasheed Wallace led the Blazers with 23 points and 14 rebounds as Portland snapped a short two-game losing streak. O'Neal led Indiana with 25 points. Artest has had trouble controlling his anger this season. In early January, he was suspended for three games without pay and fined $35,000 for hurling a television monitor and smashing a camera after a loss in New York. Later that month, he was suspended for four games without pay for a run-in with Heat coach Pat Riley and flashing an obscene gesture toward the crowd during a game in Miami. He also was suspended by his team for a game last month for smashing a framed picture of himself. Artest fouled out with 2:17 left, finishing with seven points in 17 minutes of play. Asked whether he thought he was being targeted by referees, Artest remained careful. "It was a good call," he said. "They're all good calls." Wells was a late scratch from Portland's starting lineup because of the flu. But he was pressed into service in the first quarter when his replacement, Ruben Patterson, left the floor with a right groin pull. Patterson did not return. After trailing 52-41 at the break, the closest the Pacers could come in the second half was 79-71 -- but Wallace came back with a 3-pointer. "This was a game of desperate measures for us," Blazers guard Scottie Pippen said. "I thought we played all aspects of the game very hard." Before the game, the Pacers activated rookie guard Fred Jones, who went to high school in Oregon and played for the University of Oregon. Jones had been on the injured list since Feb. 20 with patella tendinitis in his left knee. He was given a warm round of applause from the Portland fans when he came into the game in the third quarter.

Game notes
The Pacers placed guard Jamison Brewer on the injured list with a mild left shoulder strain. He was expected to be out for about two weeks, the team said. ... Pacers center Brad Miller left the game in the second half with a sore left foot.
